  "prompt": "How is the M27 IAR issued at the US Marines squad level? One for each fire-team, or mixed with the M249 SAW?",
  "response": "The M27 IAR (Infantry Automatic Rifle) is typically issued at the squad level in the US Marine Corps as part of the squad's automatic weapon capability. In the current organization, the M27 is often issued as the primary automatic weapon for fire teams, replacing the M249 Squad Automatic Weapon (SAW) in many units. \n\nIn practice, a squad might be equipped with several M27s, usually with one assigned to each fire team (there are typically three fire teams in a Marine Corps rifle squad). This allows for a more versatile and maneuverable approach to infantry firepower, as the M27's design emphasizes accuracy and capability in both semi-automatic and automatic fire.\n\nWhile some units may still retain the M249 in certain roles or configurations, the trend has been toward standardizing the M27 IAR, emphasizing its role as a primary support weapon in the fire teams. So, in general, it is common to see M27s issued to fire teams, with the M249 SAW being less common in that role as the Marine Corps continues to adapt its firepower structure.",
